description.text:
My stock stabilizers broke; the printed replacements broke, and I found myself missing the hardware that came with it all. Here's my solution!

IMPORTANT: I have yet to test this design on my Robo 3D. While I'm literally moments away from printing and testing, know that this may not work as of right now.

v2.0 Changes (9/28/16)

  • Greatly simplified the design for better printing, modification.
  • Included a "Single-body" version of the part file to save you from my lazy Solidworks tactics
  • Opened up some space so the hex nut can be removed if need be.
  • Raised the endstop holder up a little.

This thing was made with Tinkercad. Edit it online https://www.tinkercad.com/things/egNhRlBvz1T

I created this plug to mount a standard tap on my wooden rain barrel. It connects with a screw thread which has standard measures (at least in the Netherlands) of BSP 3/4" (=27mm outer diameter). The plug is tapering from 39 to 36mm such that is can be firmly pushed or hammered into the hole.

I included the scad-file so that one can easily change the plug diameters. The screw thread can be changed as well, but you should be more careful what to do.

There is no need for supports. I printed it using only 10% infill and it was solid enough for its purpose. The result was a marvelous solid and waterproof connection.

I added the Gardena connector to attach the hose to the barrel. It did fit in my tap, but it was taylor made for that purpose. I included the scad-file as well, so you may create your own connector if this one does not fit.

description.text:
This shows 500 individual pulses (about 471 seconds worth of data) of the pulsar J0034-0721 observed on January 19, 2016 with the Murchison Widefield Array telescope. The data were reduced and analyzed by PhD student Sammy McSweeney of Curtin University, in Australia.

This particular pulsar shows long "nulls" (times when no pulses at all are received) and "drifting subpulses" (miniature pulses that move diagonally across the diagram). Both of those phenomena are very poorly understood.

The pulsar rotates every 0.94 seconds, and is about 3000 light-years away in the constellation Cetus

With GizmoDorks 3mm glow-in-the-dark filament (HY-PLA-300-WHT) we needed to run the printer at 75% speed for good results.

I used the stl_tools package to convert the folded pulsar data into a 3D model. It was printed with assistance from the University of Wisconsin-Milwaukee Rapid Prototyping Lab.

The software I used is at: https://github.com/dlakaplan/singlepulse

I designed this to hold a Pokemon character I printed for a five year-old grand-daughter. The hinge is oversized to make it sturdy for use by smaller children.

Three inch (75mm) Pokeball with optional magnetic catch and stand. Thin walled (2.5mm) for maximum interior space, the design provides small holes in the bottom and ring into which pieces of filament can be inserted to act as alignment keys. There is a through hole in the button and holder to align it to the ring. Simply insert the filament into one of the pieces and cut it so that it protrudes about 2mm. Minimal cleaning was necessary for my print. The SCAD file is included to allow you to play with the design.

UPDATE adjusted hinge so that it closes properly, changed position of holes in button, holder and ring so that there are two pieces of filament holding them so they can not rotate. Ball can be completely assembled without glue.

title: Universal Smart Phone Microscope Mount Remix

description.text:
This is a remix of user Universal Camera Phone/Microscope Adapter by ggoss.

Modifications include:

  1. Accommodates 5mm hex bolts (5x25mm x3 & 5x50mm x2);
  2. Includes permanently friction-welded hex bolt retainer caps;
  3. Channels for applying hot glue which, when cool, acts as rubbery grips (eyepiece & phone grips) and;
  4. Larger frame to accommodate larger smartphones (including Wiko Pulp Fab).

We've included the SketchUp 2015 file for those wishing to edit it using SketchUp.

For more information about how and why we modified and built this mount read here: http://www.progressth.org/2016/09/3d-printing-microscopy.html

No

Yes

Notes:

The entire model shown is printed at 30% infill but the rails should probably be printed at at least 50% or more.

This requires a few extra steps.

  1. The tolerances are tight, and some sanding/filing might be needed to get the hex bolts and nuts to fit;
  2. The nuts need to be friction-welded into the knobs (or super-glued);
  3. The retaining covers need to be friction-welded (or super-glued) over the hex bolts when in place and;
  4. Apply hot glue into the channels ensuring it fills them completely. When cooled, the hot glue will act as rubbery grips, held in place by the shape of the channels.

Note on Friction Welding

Friction welding involves using a short length of 3D printing filament (PLA) placed in a small collet of a rotary tool set on its lowest speed. Use safety glasses and be mindful that no one else is around because pieces will inevitably fly. Put slight pressure on the spinning filament at the joint you are trying to weld and keep it there until the friction melds the filament then slowly create a "bead" across the joint.

It takes some practice but once you get the hang of it, it is stronger than glue, usually as good as if it were printed (sometimes stronger).

This is a very simplified but still functional Monoculight. I exhibited this "Maker Faire Edition" at the Troy Mini Maker Faire on Aug. 27, 2016. Attendees were encouraged to visit my table and build these models to take with them. This is a potentially valuable project for a STEM educational workshop.

The constituent parts are very cheap:

  • 3D printed parts:
    • Lens/screen holders (Holder.stl)
  • Paper Card stock
  • Fresnel lens magnifier cards (Credit Card 3x Magnifier or equivalent)
  • Diffuser sheet (tracing paper, wax paper or other -- some experimentation may be required to find the best material for creating a clear image)
  • Tape

Also for the assembly process you'll need:

  • 3D printed parts:
    • Tubular forming tool (Tube-Roller_OD*.stl)
    • Fresnel lens template card (Fresnel-lens-card.stl)
  • Ultra fine tip sharpie marker
  • 1" diameter heavy duty hole punch (needs to be able to punch through the plastic Fresnel lens cards. For instance: Fiskars Thick Material Circle Punch
  • Paper trimmer and scissors.

Graphically illustrated assembly directions may be printed from the file: Monoculight-Makerfaire-Instructions.pdf. Also an optional figure of an eye with inverted imaging is provided in Drawing-of-eye-with-Makey-imaged.png

Print out tube-cut-patterns-1.pdf and/or tube-cut-patterns-3.pdfonto paper cardstock. The -1 version is plain white and the -3 version includes the assembly directions (this way the instruction sheet becomes part of the project materials -- preferably make the model with the directions facing in so the outfacing side will be white).

There are two tubular forming tool STLs provided (Tube-Roller_OD*.stl). Choose the best one based on the thickness of the cardstock that you have. To determine which to use you can 3D print just a small section of each and wrap a sample card around it. Whichever tube yields a cylinder that snugly fits into the holder should be used.

3D print Fresnel-lens-card.stl. A plastic Fresnel lens card should snap fit within. Place the lens card in with the ridged prisms side toward the 1" hole in the template. Trace the circular hole using the marker through the template onto the lens. Also trace the long line adjacent to the circle onto the lens. Take the lens out of the template and use the scissors to cut the lens in two pieces along the line you drew.

Place the lens in the hole punch so the circle is well aligned with the cutting edges and punch out the lens disk. Also use the hole punch to punch out a diffuser screen disk (retina screen).

3D print two parts per model of Holder.stl.

You now have the materials necessary to follow the instructions provided in Monoculight-Makerfaire-Instructions.pdf. The lens side of the completed model can be pointed at objects of varying distance away and the tubes focussed to create a sharp inverted image on the retina screen. WARNING: the lens should never be pointed directly at the sun.

NOTE: Many people try to use the model like a telescope and put their eyes right up next to the screen. This doesn't work very well. It's much better if you view the screen by holding the model out at arm's length.

1- Download and install 3D Object Converter

3- Save each part one by one as obj (or fbx or whatever you like, I used obj and it worked fine)

title: New Prusa i3 MK1 & MK2 Spool Holder V2 - Quick Change

description.text:
02/01/2017 - Updated design, two rollers widths available and you will need four 608 skateboard bearings. The side supports have a built-in filament guides as well. There is a notch built into the rollers that will prevent the bearings from being pushed in too far. This thing works like a charm, it has been shared on the Prusa i3 Facebook group and downloaded and printed countless of times. Let me know what you thing if you print and use it!

You will want to print the nuts and bolts with a high infill (at least 50% to 75%) I have been using these bolts for a year without issues. And 13% to 20% for the rollers and supports will be fine. Print using ABS!

11/28/2016 - Updated design, clears extruder.

This is a spool holder that allows you to quickly remove and place a new spook on the printer for printing. I am not a fan of having rods or tubes and I wanted something low profile. They latch onto the frame the same way that the original Prusa i3 Spool Holder does with just about the same clearances.

I used the 608 bearing adapters myself and pressed in 608 bearings that I purchased from a local skate shop. I printed the nuts the bolts with a slightly higher infill around 30% to 40% you won't be tightening them that hard so you will be fine with that. I have printed numerous versions and haven't broken on yet. This was all printed with ABS.

You can also print and use the all plastic bearings, which also work but with the bearings it will be much smoother. Just don't tighten the nuts too much or the plastic bearings won't spin freely.

I'm sure using a flexible material for the 608 bearing adapter would be nicer, but I'm fine with how I have mine now.

The main supports I printed with 20% but I am sure that even lower will work just not too much lower than that.

title: Battery Door for Yongnuo YN465 SpeedLite

description.text:
My YN465 flash took a dive off a lightstand a few years ago and the battery door broke, I kind-of got it to stay in place and it worked until last week when it finally failed.

So I designed this replacement door, this is a new design and not a model of the original door - I made it easier to 3D print than the original design.

I only tested it on the YN465 but it will probably fit all the YN4xx models with the annoying sliding door.

The door has electrical contacts, I used a conductive band (probably copper) from an old broken power strip, there are slots in the model to hold them in place.

Print in 100% infill and support touching buildplate (the small "tooth" at the far side requires support but if you add support everywhere it will fill the little slots for the conductive bands).

I printed in PLA (because I had black PLA available), sliced with Cura and printed on my Robo3D R1+

Update

Cura decided this model does not need auto-generated support, Cura was very wrong and my batteries were very on the floor.

I've added a version with supports, the support doesn't touch the side of the door so it doesn't leave a mark when removed, use a sharp knife of a small wire cutter to remove the support from the tooth

Update 2

I wrote a long explenation but thingiverse logged me out and deleted it, so here's the really short version

  1. PLA not durable enogth, I switched to nylon, other materials (like ABS) would probably be ok

  • use writeOpenScad to write the openSCAD file
  • run the python script

USE

To change/alter/tweak the result:

  • run it.

description.text:
This is a test object for fine-tuning bed leveling and the Z endstop.

The basic object is a rectangular spiral with line width and line spacing both equal to the nozzle size (in this case 0.4 mm). It makes it easy to spot if the nozzle is at correct height: ideally, line width and line spacing should be equal when printed. If lines are wider than spacing, then the nozzle is too low. If lines are thinner than spacing, or if the object doesn't stick to the print platform, then nozzle is most likely too high.
It's quick to print and comes off the bed easily, since it's a continuous piece of plastic.

The whole test pattern consists of 9 such objects: 8 placed along print area edges and 1 in the center. This way you can easily see which way the print platform is tilted along the X and Y axis.

This is a modified version of the chocolate mold made by 2ROBOTGUY to use less plastic.  This version takes half the time to print.  This version also allows you to remove the mold pieces diagonally.

Print both sides as well as the mold clip. Brush the surface of the mold with Acetone ABS mixture to create a smooth crevice free surface. Temper your chocolate. Assemble mold by sliding the pieces into the mold clip to hold the tops together, then use a rubber band to hold the bottom of the mold together. Fill will chocolate, let cool then carefully remove the mold pieces by pulling on then diagonally. Gently tapping the mold helps to bust to release. When printed as scaled for the TOM the finished bust weighed 104 grams. For tips on working with chocolate
